H^(1/3) interpretation via Claim B:
  H = sum over odd-cycle collections 2^|C|
  = sum_{k=0}^{alpha(Omega)} f_k * 2^k  where f_k = independent sets of size k
  For n=7: H = 1 + 2*a1 + 4*a2 (only k=0,1,2)
  H^(1/3) would mix the binary layers in a non-integer way

More natural: I(2^(1/3)) = 1 + 2^(1/3)*a1 + 2^(2/3)*a2
  This is NOT an integer, but lives in Z[2^(1/3)]
  The ring Z[2^(1/3)] is a degree-3 extension of Z
  Minimal polynomial: x^3 - 2 = 0 (Eisenstein at p=2)

  2^(1/3) = 1.259921
  a1= 42, a2=  7: I(2^(1/3)) = 65.0285
  a1= 42, a2=  7: I(2^(1/3)) = 65.0285
  a1= 21, a2=  4: I(2^(1/3)) = 33.8079
  a1= 19, a2=  1: I(2^(1/3)) = 26.5259
  a1= 41, a2=  8: I(2^(1/3)) = 65.3560

The NUMBER FIELD tower:
  I(2) lives in Z
  I(omega) lives in Z[omega] = Z[(-1+sqrt(-3))/2]
  I(2^(1/3)) lives in Z[2^(1/3)]
  These are three distinct quadratic/cubic extensions of Q
  Union: I lives in Q(omega, 2^(1/3)) which has degree 6 = 2*3 over Q!
  The splitting field of x^3 - 2 is exactly Q(omega, 2^(1/3))
  Galois group: S_3 (order 6 = 2*3 = |S_3|)

======================================================================
PART 13: THE 8-9 PAIR — CONSECUTIVE POWERS AND NEAR-MISSES
======================================================================

8 = 2^3 and 9 = 3^2: the ONLY consecutive perfect powers (Catalan/Mihailescu)

In tournament theory:
  n=8: homological inflection (beta_3>1, seesaw breaks)
  n=9: I.P. real-roots first fail (THM-025 counterexample)
  The failures at 8 and 9 are DIFFERENT IN KIND:
    n=8: topological (path homology)
    n=9: algebraic (independence polynomial roots)

H values at n=8 and n=9:

  Sample H values at n=7:
    Min H = 5, Max H = 159, Mean = 82.2

  H=8 is impossible (H always odd)
  H=9 = 1 + 2*4 + 4*0 (a1=4, a2=0) — achievable at n>=5

The Catalan equation x^p - y^q = 1:
  3^2 - 2^3 = 1
  Tournament version: I(3) - I(2) = step = a1 + 5*a2
  When does I(3) - I(2) = 1?
    a1 + 5*a2 = 1 => a1=1, a2=0
    This means exactly 1 odd cycle, 0 disjoint pairs
    H = I(2) = 1 + 2 = 3, I(3) = 1 + 3 = 4
    So the 'Catalan' step I(3)-I(2)=1 forces H=3 (smallest non-trivial)

  When does I(3)^2 - I(2)^3 = 1? (actual Catalan structure)

======================================================================
PART 14: SYNTHESIS — THE TRINITY OF OPERATIONS ON {2,3}
======================================================================

The three binary operations on the pair (2, 3):

  ADDITION:        2 + 3 = 5    (prime, commutative)
  MULTIPLICATION:  2 * 3 = 6    (composite = 2*3, commutative)
  EXPONENTIATION:  2 ^ 3 = 8    (= 2^3, NON-commutative)
                   3 ^ 2 = 9    (= 3^2)

  Outputs: {5, 6, 8, 9} (four numbers from three operations)

Tournament theory meaning:
  5 = 2+3: first n with non-trivial Omega(T); I(Omega,x) quadratic
  6 = 2*3: first n with beta_3 > 0; multiplicative structure emerges
  8 = 2^3: inflection point; homological properties fail
  9 = 3^2: algebraic properties fail (real roots); claw-free fails

The ORDERED structure:
  5 < 6 < 8 < 9
  + < * < ^(2,3) < ^(3,2)
  Each operation produces a LARGER result on (2,3)
  The gap pattern: 6-5=1, 8-6=2, 9-8=1
  Symmetric: gaps are 1, 2, 1 (palindromic!)

Cyclotomic connections:
  Phi_1(2) = 1    (2-1)
  Phi_2(2) = 3    (2+1)
  Phi_3(2) = 7    (2^2+2+1)
  Phi_4(2) = 5    (2^2+1)
  Phi_5(2) = 31   (2^4+2^3+2^2+2+1)
  Phi_6(2) = 3    (2^2-2+1)
  Phi_8(2) = 17   (2^4+1)
  Phi_9(2) = 73   (2^6+2^3+1)

  Products:
  2^1 - 1 = 1  = Phi_1(2)
  2^2 - 1 = 3  = Phi_1(2)*Phi_2(2) = 1*3
  2^3 - 1 = 7  = Phi_1(2)*Phi_3(2) = 1*7
  2^6 - 1 = 63 = Phi_1*Phi_2*Phi_3*Phi_6 = 1*3*7*3 = 63
  Note: 63 = 2^6 - 1 is in our forbidden set!
  2^6 = 64, and 63 = forbidden H, and 6 = 2*3
  So 2^(2*3) - 1 is forbidden!

The NUMBER FIELD synthesis:
  Q(omega, 2^(1/3)) is the splitting field of x^3 - 2
  Degree [Q(omega, 2^(1/3)) : Q] = 6 = 2*3
  Galois group = S_3, order 6 = 3! = 2*3
  The tournament independence polynomial I(x) = 1 + a1*x + a2*x^2
  has degree 2 (at n=7), so its splitting field is at most degree 2 over Q
  But evaluating I at 2^(1/3) yields elements of the DEGREE 6 field
  Combining all tournament evaluations requires the full S_3 Galois group

Final observation: FIVE numbers summarize everything
  2, 3, 5=2+3, 6=2*3, 7=Phi_3(2)=2^2+2+1
  These are the first 5 primes: 2, 3, 5, 7 (plus 6=2*3)
  And n=7 is where our quadratic I.P. theory is most complete
  At n=7: alpha(Omega) = 2 always, so I(x) is quadratic
  The theory 'lives' in the quadratic world of 2 and 3

  Beyond n=7: I(x) can be cubic or higher
  The quadratic era ends, the cubic era begins
  Exponentiation (2^3=8) marks this transition
  Just as octonions (dim 2^3=8) end the division algebra era

